Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that checks for a key "favoriteGames" in local storage, loads it as a JSON list of objects, and checks if any of the objects have the attribute `.project` set to `"is_favorite"`. Depending on the result, it displays a thumbs up or thumbs down on the page.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Favorite Games Checker</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            text-align: center;
            margin-top: 50px;
        }
        .thumbs-up {
            font-size: 100px;
            color: green;
        }
        .thumbs-down {
            font-size: 100px;
            color: red;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="result"></div>

    <script>
        // Function to check local storage and display thumbs
        function checkFavoriteGames() {
            const favoriteGames = localStorage.getItem("favoriteGames");
            const resultDiv = document.getElementById("result");

            if (favoriteGames) {
                const gamesList = JSON.parse(favoriteGames);
                const isFavorite = gamesList.some(game => game.project === "is_favorite");

                if (isFavorite) {
                    resultDiv.innerHTML = '<div class="thumbs-up">üëç</div>';
                } else {
                    resultDiv.innerHTML = '<div class="thumbs-down">üëé</div>';
                }
            } else {
                resultDiv.innerHTML = '<div class="thumbs-down">üëé</div>';
            }
        }

        // Call the function on page load
        window.onload = checkFavoriteGames;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The HTML contains a `div` with the ID `result` where the thumbs up or down will be displayed.
- **CSS Styles**: Basic styles are provided to center the text and set colors for thumbs up and down.
- **JavaScript Logic**:
  - The script retrieves the `favoriteGames` from local storage.
  - It checks if the key exists and parses it as JSON.
  - It uses the `some` method to check if any game object has the `project` attribute set to `"is_favorite"`.
  - Depending on the result, it updates the `resultDiv` with either a thumbs up or thumbs down emoji.

### Usage:
To test this code, you can copy it into an HTML file and open it in a web browser. Make sure to set the `favoriteGames` in local storage for testing. You can do this in the browser's console:

```javascript
localStorage.setItem("favoriteGames", JSON.stringify([{ project: "is_favorite" }, { project: "not_favorite" }]));
```

This will set the `favoriteGames` key with a sample array of game objects. Refresh the page to see the thumbs up displayed.
